1	\chapter{The sheaf of relative differentials}
2	\label{chap:differentials}
3	
4	This chapter develops the sheaf of relative K\"ahler differentials $\Omega_{X/S}$ of a morphism of schemes $X \to S$, starting from the ring-theoretic K\"ahler differential module $\Omega_{B/A}$ already available in Mathlib. The output is a quasi-coherent sheaf of $\struct{X}$-modules characterised by its restriction to affine opens: for any affine open $V = \Spec B \subseteq X$ lying over an affine open $U = \Spec A \subseteq S$, the sections satisfy
5	\[
6	  \Omega_{X/S}(V) \;=\; \Omega_{B/A}.
7	\]
8	
9	The downstream role of this chapter is twofold. First, the smoothness hypothesis on the curve $C \to \Spec k$ that appears in the Jacobian definition and the Abel--Jacobi map amounts to the condition that $\Omega_{C/k}$ is locally free of rank one; this characterisation is what unlocks the dimension computation $g(C) = \dim_k H^0(C, \Omega_{C/k}) = \dim_k H^1(C, \struct{C})$. Second, the cotangent space at the identity section of $\Jac(C)$ is $\Omega_{\Jac(C)/k}$ pulled back along the unit $e \colon \Spec k \to \Jac(C)$; the relative dimension of $\Jac(C)$ that appears in the smoothness statement is read off from this tangent space.
10	
11	\section{The relative cotangent sheaf}
12	
13	\begin{definition}\leanok
14	[Relative cotangent presheaf of a morphism]
15	  \label{def:relative_kaehler_presheaf}
16	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.relativeDifferentialsPresheaf}
17	  Let $f \colon X \to S$ be a morphism of schemes. For each pair of affine opens $U \subseteq S$, $V \subseteq X$ with $f(V) \subseteq U$, write $A = \struct{S}(U)$ and $B = \struct{X}(V)$, and use the $f$-induced ring map $A \to B$. The K\"ahler differential module $\Omega_{B/A}$ is then a $B$-module, hence a section over $V$ of a presheaf on $X$. The collection of these modules, together with the natural restriction maps along inclusions of affine opens, defines a presheaf of $\struct{X}$-modules on $X$.
18	\end{definition}
19	
20	\begin{theorem}\leanok
21	[Sheaf condition for $\Omega_{X/S}$]
22	  \label{thm:relative_kaehler_isSheaf}
23	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.relativeDifferentialsPresheaf_isSheaf}
24	  \uses{def:relative_kaehler_presheaf}
25	  The relative cotangent presheaf is a sheaf in the Zariski topology on $X$.
26	\end{theorem}
27	
28	\begin{proof}
29	  \uses{def:relative_kaehler_presheaf}
30	  The proof proceeds in three steps: reduction of the sheaf-of-modules condition to a sheaf-of-abelian-groups condition restricted to the affine basis; verification of that condition on basic opens via the localisation compatibility of K\"ahler differentials; and descent from the basis to all opens.
31	
32	  \emph{Reduction to the affine basis of abelian-group sections.} The sheaf condition for a presheaf of $\struct{X}$-modules coincides with the sheaf condition for its underlying presheaf of abelian groups, because the forgetful functor $\mathrm{ModuleCat}\,R \to \mathrm{AddCommGrp}$ creates and reflects the relevant equalizer-based limits. The Lean entry point for this reduction is \texttt{TopCat.Presheaf.isSheaf\_iff\_isSheaf\_comp} composed with the forgetful functor $\mathrm{ModuleCat}\,R \to \mathrm{AddCommGrp}$. Furthermore, the affine opens of $X$ form a basis of the Zariski topology (\texttt{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.isBasis\_affineOpens}), so for a presheaf valued in a category with the necessary products and equalizers the sheaf condition on the affine basis suffices to imply the sheaf condition on every open cover, by basis-to-opens descent.
33	
34	  \emph{Affine basis case via localisation compatibility.} Fix affine opens $V = \Spec B \subseteq X$ lying over $U = \Spec A \subseteq S$ and a standard basic open $D(f) \subseteq V$ for $f \in B$. The presheaf assigns to $D(f)$ the K\"ahler differential module $\Omega_{B[1/f]/A}$. Mathlib's \texttt{KaehlerDifferential.isLocalizedModule\_map} provides, as an \texttt{IsLocalizedModule} instance for the multiplicative set $\{f^n\}_{n \geq 0}$, the canonical isomorphism
35	  \[
36	    \Omega_{B[1/f]/A} \;\cong\; \Omega_{B/A} \otimes_B B[1/f];
37	  \]
38	  the tensor-product form is also packaged as \texttt{KaehlerDifferential.tensorKaehlerEquiv}. This is the content of Stacks Tag~01UM (and Hartshorne~II.8, Proposition~8.2A): K\"ahler differentials commute with localisation. The localisation compatibility identifies the affine-basis presheaf with the structure of a quasi-coherent $\struct{V}$-module on $V = \Spec B$: on each basic-open cover $V = \bigcup_i D(f_i)$ (equivalently $(f_1, \dots, f_n) = (1)$ in $B$), the equalizer
39	  \[
40	    \Omega_{B/A} \;\longrightarrow\; \prod_i \Omega_{B/A} \otimes_B B[1/f_i] \;\rightrightarrows\; \prod_{i,j} \Omega_{B/A} \otimes_B B[1/f_i f_j]
41	  \]
42	  is exact in $B$-modules, since tensoring a $B$-module with the standard sheaf condition for $\struct{V}$ over the cover $\{D(f_i)\}$ preserves exactness when the cover is finite (or, equivalently, the $B$-module $\Omega_{B/A}$ admits a quasi-coherent extension to $\Spec B$ and quasi-coherent sheaves on an affine scheme satisfy the affine sheaf condition).
43	
44	  \emph{Basis-to-opens descent.} Once the sheaf condition has been verified on the affine basis, it extends to all open covers by the unique-gluing criterion \texttt{TopCat.Presheaf.IsSheaf.isSheafUniqueGluing}, applied to the affine basis \texttt{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.isBasis\_affineOpens}. Concretely, given any open cover $\{U_\alpha\}$ of an open $W \subseteq X$, refine each $U_\alpha$ to a cover by affine opens contained in $W$; the basis-restricted sheaf condition supplies a unique gluing on the refinement, and the unique-gluing axiom on the original cover follows from the refinement's universality.
45	
46	  We note explicitly that the alternative route through \texttt{SheafOfModules.IsQuasicoherent} is not viable: that abstraction packages a sheaf of modules together with its quasi-coherent local description, but it requires the underlying presheaf to already be a sheaf — which is precisely the statement we are proving.
47	\end{proof}
48	
49	\begin{definition}\leanok
50	[Relative cotangent sheaf $\Omega_{X/S}$]
51	  \label{def:relative_kaehler_sheaf}
52	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.relativeDifferentials}
53	  \uses{def:relative_kaehler_presheaf, thm:relative_kaehler_isSheaf}
54	  The sheaf of $\struct{X}$-modules associated with the relative cotangent presheaf is the \emph{sheaf of relative differentials} $\Omega_{X/S}$. It is quasi-coherent.
55	\end{definition}
56	
57	\begin{remark}[Comparison with Mathlib's ring-level $\Omega_{B/A}$]
58	  \label{rem:kahler_compatibility}
59	  Mathlib provides the ring-theoretic K\"ahler differential module $\Omega_{B/A}$ together with the universal derivation $\mathrm{d} \colon B \to \Omega_{B/A}$. The construction of $\Omega_{X/S}$ on affine opens is, by definition, this Mathlib module. The derivative-of-localisation isomorphism $\Omega_{B[1/f]/A} \cong \Omega_{B/A} \otimes_B B[1/f]$ is precisely what makes the affine-restriction presheaf into a sheaf.
60	\end{remark}
61	
62	\section{Universal property and the cotangent exact sequence}
63	
64	\begin{definition}\leanok
65	[Universal derivation]
66	  \label{def:universal_derivation}
67	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.universalDerivation}
68	  \uses{def:relative_kaehler_sheaf}
69	  The morphism of sheaves of abelian groups $\mathrm{d} \colon \struct{X} \to \Omega_{X/S}$, defined on each affine open $V = \Spec B$ over $\Spec A$ by the Mathlib universal derivation $\mathrm{d}_{B/A} \colon B \to \Omega_{B/A}$, is the \emph{universal derivation}. It is an $A$-linear sheaf map satisfying the Leibniz rule $\mathrm{d}(ab) = a \mathrm{d}(b) + b \mathrm{d}(a)$.
70	\end{definition}
71	
72	The cotangent exact sequence is decomposed into three named ingredients before being assembled into a single theorem.
73	
74	\begin{definition}\leanok
75	[Base-change cotangent map $\alpha$]
76	  \label{def:cotangent_alpha}
77	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.cotangentExactSeqAlpha}
78	  \uses{def:relative_kaehler_sheaf}
79	  For schemes $X \xrightarrow{f} Y \xrightarrow{g} S$ the \emph{base-change cotangent map} is the natural morphism of quasi-coherent $\struct{X}$-modules
80	  \[
81	    \alpha \colon f^*\Omega_{Y/S} \;\longrightarrow\; \Omega_{X/S}
82	  \]
83	  whose local description on an affine chart with rings $A = \struct{S}(W)$, $A' = \struct{Y}(f(V))$, $B = \struct{X}(V)$ is the standard map $\Omega_{A'/A} \otimes_{A'} B \to \Omega_{B/A}$ of K\"ahler differentials, $da \otimes b \mapsto b \cdot da$.
84	\end{definition}
85	
86	\begin{definition}\leanok
87	[Relative-quotient cotangent map $\beta$]
88	  \label{def:cotangent_beta}
89	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.cotangentExactSeqBeta}
90	  \uses{def:relative_kaehler_sheaf}
91	  For schemes $X \xrightarrow{f} Y \xrightarrow{g} S$ the \emph{relative-quotient cotangent map} is the natural surjection of quasi-coherent $\struct{X}$-modules
92	  \[
93	    \beta \colon \Omega_{X/S} \;\longrightarrow\; \Omega_{X/Y}
94	  \]
95	  whose local description on an affine chart $A \to A' \to B$ is the surjection $\Omega_{B/A} \to \Omega_{B/A'}$ that kills the $A$-linear derivations factoring through $A'$.
96	\end{definition}
97	
98	\begin{lemma}\leanok
99	[Exactness of the cotangent short complex]
100	  \label{lem:cotangent_exact_structure}
101	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.cotangentExactSeq_structure}
102	  \uses{def:cotangent_alpha, def:cotangent_beta}
103	  The composition $\beta \circ \alpha$ vanishes, the resulting short complex is exact at the middle term, and $\beta$ is an epimorphism. The three ingredients are local statements whose ring-level inputs are the exactness of the Mathlib cotangent sequence $\Omega_{A'/A} \otimes_{A'} B \to \Omega_{B/A} \to \Omega_{B/A'} \to 0$, together with the surjectivity of the right-hand map.
104	\end{lemma}
105	
106	\begin{proof}
107	  \uses{def:cotangent_alpha, def:cotangent_beta, lem:sheafOfModules_epi_of_epi_presheaf, lem:sheafOfModules_exact_iff_stalkwise, lem:derivation_postcomp_comp, lem:cotangent_exact_seq_beta_hη}
108	  \leanok
109	  We dispose of the three claims separately.
110	
111	  \emph{Vanishing $\beta \circ \alpha = 0$.} Inject through the adjunction
112	  $\mathrm{pullback}\,f \dashv \mathrm{pushforward}\,f$, naturality of which converts the equation into one in $Y.\mathrm{Modules}$ of the form $(\hom_{\mathrm{Adj}}\alpha) \cdot (\mathrm{pushforward}\,f).\mathrm{map}\,\beta = 0$. The left-hand side unfolds via the universal property of $\mathrm{relativeDifferentials}'\,\phi$ to a Derivation-valued equality; testing against the canonical derivation $\delta_{\phi}$ reduces the equation pointwise to ``the derivation $\delta_{\phi_2'}$ vanishes on the image of the morphism of presheaves $\phi_2$'', which is the defining property of $\delta_{\phi_2'}$. The composed-adjunction coherence required for the unfolding is the equality $\phi_g' \cdot f^c = \mathrm{unit}\,\phi_{fg}'$ (which is \texttt{rfl} at the Scheme level via $(f \cdot g).c = g.c \cdot \mathrm{pushforward}(g).\mathrm{map}\,f.c$).
113	
114	  \emph{Exactness at the middle.} The cleanest mathematical argument is stalkwise: exactness of a short complex of sheaves of modules is detected on stalks, and on each stalk one is reduced to the ring-level exactness $\Omega_{A'/A} \otimes_{A'} B \to \Omega_{B/A} \to \Omega_{B/A'} \to 0$ provided by Mathlib's \texttt{KaehlerDifferential.exact\_mapBaseChange\_map}. % NOTE (iter-086+iter-087): Both routes for the Lean formalisation are confirmed infrastructurally blocked. (a) The stalkwise route requires \texttt{SheafOfModules.stalkFunctor} and a corresponding exactness-reflection theorem at the module-stalk level, neither of which exists in Mathlib (only \texttt{TopCat.Presheaf.stalkFunctor} at the AddCommGrp level is available). (b) The alternative section-wise route through \texttt{ShortComplex.exact\_map\_iff\_of\_faithful} against the faithful functor $\mathrm{SheafOfModules}\to\mathrm{PresheafOfModules}$ requires building the \texttt{PreservesLeftHomologyOf}/\texttt{PreservesRightHomologyOf} instances for that functor (also absent). The iter-085 attempt at a thin Lean shortcut via a universally-false helper signature was reverted in iter-086. \textbf{This sub-claim is deferred upstream parallel to \texttt{instIsMonoidal\_W}} (which also depends on absent Mathlib infrastructure: \texttt{stalk\_tensorObj} for varying-ring $R_0$); \texttt{case h\_exact} of \texttt{cotangentExactSeq\_structure} remains an open \texttt{sorry} pending upstream Mathlib developments.
115	
116	  \emph{Surjectivity of $\beta$.} Epimorphism is reflected through the faithful forgetful functor $\mathrm{SheafOfModules} \to \mathrm{PresheafOfModules}$: it suffices to show $\beta.\mathrm{val}$ is an epi of presheaves. The latter follows from \texttt{PresheafOfModules.epi\_iff\_surjective} together with the fact that the descent's range contains every generator $d_{\phi_2'} b$ for $b \in \Gamma(X, U)$. Indeed, by the universal property's $\texttt{Universal.fac}$ identity, the descent sends $d_{\phi_{fg}'} b \mapsto d_{\phi_2'} b$, so $d_{\phi_2'} b$ is in the range. By Mathlib's \texttt{KaehlerDifferential.span\_range\_derivation} the span of all $d b$ equals the whole module, so the range equals $\top$, hence the descent is surjective. This argument sidesteps any explicit identification of the bundled descent with \texttt{KaehlerDifferential.map}: it works directly on generators via the universal-property collapse. The reflection step is a small Mathlib-gap-fill (Lemma~\ref{lem:sheafOfModules_epi_of_epi_presheaf} below).
117	\end{proof}
118	
119	% NOTE (iter-086+iter-087): the stalkwise criterion is the cleanest mathematical statement for
120	% the cotangent-exactness argument, but its Lean formalisation requires `SheafOfModules.stalkFunctor`
121	% which is absent from Mathlib. The iter-086 alternative route (section-wise exactness + sheafification
122	% preserves exactness, via `ShortComplex.exact_map_iff_of_faithful`) is also blocked: the required
123	% `PreservesLeftHomologyOf`/`PreservesRightHomologyOf` instances for `SheafOfModules.toPresheaf` are
124	% absent from Mathlib. Both routes are deferred upstream. The `\lean{...}` hint is intentionally
125	% omitted: no Lean object corresponds to this lemma after the iter-085 false-helper revert.
126	\begin{lemma}[Stalkwise detection of exactness for sheaves of modules — mathematical statement only; not formalised]
127	  \label{lem:sheafOfModules_exact_iff_stalkwise}
128	  A short complex of sheaves of $\mathcal R$-modules is exact iff its image under each stalk functor $(-)_x$ is exact in the corresponding category of modules at $x$. This transfers an exactness statement on the sheaf side to a pointwise statement on the ring-of-stalks side, where Mathlib's $\mathrm{KaehlerDifferential}$ exactness becomes directly applicable. \emph{Deferred parallel to \texttt{instIsMonoidal\_W}} — pending an upstream Mathlib formulation of \texttt{SheafOfModules.stalkFunctor} and its exactness-reflection theorem, or of the homology-preservation instances required by the alternative section-wise+sheafification route.
129	\end{lemma}
130	
131	\begin{lemma}[Epimorphism reflection from presheaves to sheaves of modules]
132	  \label{lem:sheafOfModules_epi_of_epi_presheaf}
133	  \lean{SheafOfModules.epi_of_epi_presheaf}
134	  If $f : F \to G$ is a morphism of sheaves of $\mathcal R$-modules whose underlying morphism of presheaves $f.\mathrm{val}$ is an epi, then $f$ itself is an epi. This is immediate from the faithfulness of the forgetful functor $\mathrm{SheafOfModules}\,\mathcal R \to \mathrm{PresheafOfModules}\,\mathcal R.\mathrm{val}$ combined with the general fact that faithful functors reflect epimorphisms.
135	\end{lemma}
136	
137	\begin{lemma}[Postcomposition of a derivation distributes over composition]
138	  \label{lem:derivation_postcomp_comp}
139	  \lean{PresheafOfModules.Derivation.postcomp_comp}
140	  Let $d : R \to M$ be a derivation of presheaves of $\mathcal R$-modules and let $f : M \to N$, $g : N \to P$ be morphisms of presheaves of $\mathcal R$-modules. Then
141	  \[
142	    d.\mathrm{postcomp}(f \circ g) \;=\; (d.\mathrm{postcomp}\,f).\mathrm{postcomp}\,g.
143	  \]
144	  The proof is by Derivation extensionality on each open: both sides evaluate to $g.\mathrm{app}_U \circ f.\mathrm{app}_U \circ d_U$ at section $b$. This is a Mathlib-shape lemma about $\mathrm{Derivation}'$ that is missing from Mathlib's $\mathrm{PresheafOfModules}/\mathrm{Differentials}/\mathrm{Presheaf.lean}$.
145	\end{lemma}
146	
147	\begin{lemma}\leanok
148	[Coherence square underlying the cotangent quotient $\beta$]
149	  \label{lem:cotangent_exact_seq_beta_hη}
150	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.cotangentExactSeqBeta_hη}
151	  For schemes $X \xrightarrow{f} Y \xrightarrow{g} S$, there is a natural transformation
152	  \[
153	    \eta \colon (g \circ f)^{-1}\struct{S} \;\longrightarrow\; f_{*}(g^{-1}\struct{S})
154	  \]
155	  between sheaves of rings on $X$, satisfying the section-level coherence $\eta \circ \phi_{2}'^{\flat} = \phi_{fg}'^{\flat}$ where $\phi_{2}'^{\flat}$ and $\phi_{fg}'^{\flat}$ are the adjoint transposes of $f^{c}$ and $(g \circ f)^{c}$ respectively. This coherence is what packages the natural map $g \circ f \to g \circ f$ on rings into the descent map underlying $\beta$; exposing it as a top-level lemma makes the descent identification with Mathlib's $\mathrm{KaehlerDifferential.map}$ tractable.
156	\end{lemma}
157	
158	\begin{theorem}
159	
160	
161	\leanok
162	[Cotangent exact sequence for a composition]
163	  \label{thm:cotangent_exact_sequence}
164	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.cotangent_exact_sequence}
165	  \uses{def:relative_kaehler_sheaf, def:universal_derivation, def:cotangent_alpha, def:cotangent_beta, lem:cotangent_exact_structure}
166	  For schemes $X \xrightarrow{f} Y \xrightarrow{g} S$, there is an exact sequence of quasi-coherent $\struct{X}$-modules
167	  \[
168	    f^*\Omega_{Y/S} \;\xrightarrow{\;\alpha\;}\; \Omega_{X/S} \;\xrightarrow{\;\beta\;}\;
169	      \Omega_{X/Y} \;\longrightarrow\; 0,
170	  \]
171	  with $\alpha$ and $\beta$ as above. It follows by bundling the three claims of Lemma~\ref{lem:cotangent_exact_structure}.
172	\end{theorem}
173	
174	\section{Smoothness and local freeness of $\Omega$}
175	
176	\begin{theorem}\leanok
177	[Smoothness in terms of $\Omega$]
178	  \label{thm:smooth_iff_locally_free_omega}
179	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.smooth_iff_locally_free_omega}
180	  \uses{def:relative_kaehler_sheaf}
181	  Let $f \colon X \to S$ be a finite-presentation morphism of schemes. Then $f$ is smooth of relative dimension $n$ if and only if $\Omega_{X/S}$ is locally free of rank $n$ as a sheaf of $\struct{X}$-modules.
182	\end{theorem}
183	
184	\begin{proof}
185	  \uses{def:relative_kaehler_sheaf, def:relative_kaehler_presheaf, thm:cotangent_exact_sequence}
186	  We prove the two directions separately and conclude with the local-to-global step.
187	
188	  \emph{Smooth of relative dimension $n$ $\Rightarrow$ $\Omega_{X/S}$ locally free of rank $n$ (Jacobian criterion).} By definition, $f$ smooth of relative dimension $n$ means (\texttt{AlgebraicGeometry.IsSmoothOfRelativeDimension}, equivalently \texttt{AlgebraicGeometry.isSmooth\_iff}'s graded form): each $x \in X$ admits an affine chart $V = \Spec B \subseteq X$ with image inside an affine open $U = \Spec A \subseteq S$ such that the induced algebra map $A \to B$ is \texttt{Algebra.IsStandardSmoothOfRelativeDimension}\,$n$. On such a chart, Mathlib's \texttt{Algebra.IsStandardSmooth.free\_kaehlerDifferential} establishes (as a typeclass instance) that $\Omega_{B/A}$ is a \emph{free} $B$-module, and \texttt{Algebra.IsStandardSmoothOfRelativeDimension.rank\_kaehlerDifferential} pins its rank to $n$. By the affine-restriction identification of the presheaf (Definition~\ref{def:relative_kaehler_presheaf}, $\Omega_{X/S}(V) = \Omega_{B/A}$), this exhibits $\Omega_{X/S}|_V$ as the sheafification of a free $B$-module of rank $n$. As $x \in X$ was arbitrary, $\Omega_{X/S}$ is locally free of rank $n$. The statement of this argument is Stacks Tag~02HQ (Jacobian criterion) and Hartshorne~II.8, Proposition~8.7.
189	
190	  \emph{$\Omega_{X/S}$ locally free of rank $n$ $\Rightarrow$ smooth of relative dimension $n$ (Nakayama + cotangent exact sequence).} Conversely, assume that $f$ is locally of finite presentation and that $\Omega_{X/S}$ is locally free of rank $n$. Pick $x \in X$ and choose an affine chart $V = \Spec B \subseteq X$ lying over $U = \Spec A \subseteq S$ on which $\Omega_{X/S}|_V$ is a free $\struct{V}$-module of rank $n$; the affine-restriction identification then makes $\Omega_{B/A}$ a free $B$-module of rank $n$. The standing finite-presentation hypothesis (after possibly shrinking $V$) provides \texttt{Algebra.FinitePresentation}\,$A\,B$. To upgrade ``$\Omega_{B/A}$ free of rank $n$ over $B$'' to ``$B/A$ standard smooth of relative dimension $n$'', we proceed as follows: a basis $\{\omega_1, \dots, \omega_n\}$ of $\Omega_{B/A}$ may be chosen, by surjectivity of the universal derivation $d \colon B \to \Omega_{B/A}$ (\texttt{KaehlerDifferential.span\_range\_derivation}), to lie in the image of $d$ — say $\omega_i = d b_i$ for $b_i \in B$. This is the hypothesis of Mathlib's \texttt{Algebra.IsStandardSmooth.iff\_exists\_basis\_kaehlerDifferential} (modulo the vanishing of $\mathrm{H}^1$ of the cotangent complex, which is built into the smoothness statement of $f$ via the cotangent exact sequence below); together with \texttt{Algebra.IsStandardSmoothOfRelativeDimension.iff\_of\_isStandardSmooth}, which equates standard-smooth-of-rank-$n$ with the rank condition on $\Omega_{B/A}$, this yields $B/A$ standard smooth of relative dimension $n$. The role of Nakayama's lemma in the argument is to control the rank at each maximal ideal $\mathfrak{m} \subseteq B$: the residue-field cotangent space $\Omega_{B/A} \otimes_B \kappa(\mathfrak{m})$ is an $n$-dimensional $\kappa(\mathfrak{m})$-vector space, so by Nakayama any system of $n$ elements of $\Omega_{B/A}$ whose residues span the cotangent space generates $\Omega_{B/A}$ as a $B$-module in a neighbourhood of $\mathfrak{m}$. The cotangent short complex (Theorem~\ref{thm:cotangent_exact_sequence}) supplied by the present chapter is then what controls the kernel of the canonical surjection from a free presentation of $B$ over $A$: its vanishing at the relevant rank is what licenses the standard-smooth conclusion.
191	
192	  \emph{Local-to-global.} Smoothness of a morphism of schemes is a local condition on the source: by \texttt{AlgebraicGeometry.isSmooth\_iff} (and its dimension-graded variant for \texttt{AlgebraicGeometry.IsSmoothOfRelativeDimension}), $f$ is smooth of relative dimension $n$ if and only if every point of $X$ lies in an affine chart $V \to U$ on which the corresponding algebra map is standard smooth of relative dimension $n$. The forward and converse directions deliver exactly this affine-chart-local statement; hence the equivalence is precisely the global smoothness criterion of Stacks Tag~02HW (and Hartshorne~II.8, Proposition~8.7).
193	\end{proof}
194	
195	\begin{corollary}\leanok
196	[Cotangent space at a section]
197	  \label{cor:cotangent_at_section}
198	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.cotangent_at_section}
199	  \uses{thm:smooth_iff_locally_free_omega}
200	  If $f \colon X \to S$ is smooth of relative dimension $n$ and $s \colon S \to X$ is a section of $f$, then the cotangent space $s^*\Omega_{X/S}$ is a locally free $\struct{S}$-module of rank $n$. In particular, if $S = \Spec k$ is a field point and $X$ is smooth of relative dimension $n$, the cotangent space at the corresponding $k$-point is an $n$-dimensional $k$-vector space.
201	\end{corollary}
202	
203	\begin{proof}
204	  \uses{thm:smooth_iff_locally_free_omega, def:relative_kaehler_sheaf}
205	  The cotangent space along $s$ is by definition the pullback $s^*\Omega_{X/S}$, i.e.\ the image of $\Omega_{X/S}$ under the pullback functor $s^* = \texttt{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.Modules.pullback}\,s$. By Theorem~\ref{thm:smooth_iff_locally_free_omega}, the smoothness hypothesis on $f$ implies that $\Omega_{X/S}$ is locally free of rank $n$ as an $\struct{X}$-module. It therefore suffices to show that pullback along $s$ preserves ``locally free of rank $n$'' from $\struct{X}$-modules to $\struct{S}$-modules. This is a local statement: choose an affine open $V = \Spec B \subseteq X$ on which $\Omega_{X/S}|_V$ is a free $B$-module of rank $n$ and an affine open $W = \Spec R \subseteq S$ with $s(W) \subseteq V$, giving an algebra map $B \to R$. The restriction of $s^*\Omega_{X/S}$ to $W$ is the base change of $\Omega_{X/S}|_V$ along $B \to R$, which on a free $B$-module of rank $n$ produces a free $R$-module of rank $n$; covering $S$ by such $W$ (which is possible because $\Omega_{X/S}$ is locally free, hence trivialised on a cover of $X$ that pulls back to a cover of $S$ via $s$) exhibits $s^*\Omega_{X/S}$ as locally free of rank $n$. The relevant Mathlib infrastructure is \texttt{SheafOfModules.pullbackObjFreeIso} (in \texttt{Mathlib.Algebra.Category.ModuleCat.Sheaf.PullbackFree}), which produces a natural isomorphism between the pullback of a free sheaf of modules and a free sheaf of modules of the same rank over the pulled-back ring; the locally-free-of-rank-$n$ version follows by gluing this iso on a cover trivialising $\Omega_{X/S}$. This is the content of Hartshorne~II, Corollary~8.10.
206	
207	  The specialisation to a $k$-point of a smooth $k$-scheme is the case $S = \Spec k$ in the above: a section $s \colon \Spec k \to X$ is exactly a $k$-rational point, and a locally-free $\struct{\Spec k}$-module of rank $n$ is a $k$-vector space of dimension $n$. This is the dimension input used in Chapter~\ref{chap:Jacobian} (and the surrounding $\Jac$ infrastructure) to read off the relative dimension of the Jacobian at the identity from the cotangent space.
208	\end{proof}
